## Start here

Run every backend command through **uv** (`uv run …`): the `terp` CLI and the
project's Python live in the local `.venv`, not on the global PATH — a bare `terp`
or `python` will not resolve.

- **`uv run terp guide`** / **`uv run terp guide <topic>`** — the authoring guide
  (module, service, policy, ownership, tenancy, events, capability, migrations, rules,
  frontend, dataview, forms).
- **`uv run terp verify`** — the one-command gate: runs the declared verification
  profile (`--profile quick` for per-edit static checks, `--profile full` for the
  merge bar CI enforces, `--profile release` before shipping). `--list` shows what a
  profile runs; `--format json` emits the machine envelope with every check's
  Terp Standard check report embedded.
- **`uv run terp check`** / **`uv run pytest`** — the gate is the source of truth.
  Green means compliant; red names the fix. `uv run terp check --format json` emits
  structured violations (rule, file, line, message, and the `uv run terp guide` fix
  recipe) for tools and agents; `--format check-report` emits the Terp Standard
  check-report document (catalog-attributed findings + the evaluated-rule inventory).
- **`uv run terp dev`** — run the API (:8000) and frontend (:5173) together, with an
  OpenAPI preflight so the typed client stays current.
- **`uv run terp new module <name>`** — scaffold the five slots.
  **`uv run terp inspect control-plane`** — your roles, permissions, and per-module
  authority map.

## Runtime environment variables

The app declares its own run-time variables in the checked-in
`environment.schema.json`; Studio renders exactly those declarations into the
per-environment `.app.env`. When a feature adds or removes a backend run-time
variable, update the manifest in the same change:

- Preserve existing declarations and declare only variables the app actually reads.
- Names are UPPER_SNAKE (`^[A-Z][A-Z0-9_]{0,63}$`). Never shadow platform-owned
  `SECRET_KEY`, `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`, `DATABASE_URL`, `ENVIRONMENT`, `WEB_PORT`, or
  `BACKEND_CORS_ORIGINS`; never put frontend build-time `VITE_*` values here.
- Mark tokens, passwords, API keys and client secrets with `"format": "secret"`.
  Never write secret values into the manifest, `.env`, source, tests, prompts or logs.
- Do not create/edit `.app.env`; Studio owns environment-specific values and renders it.
- Add concise titles/descriptions; use `required` only when the app cannot operate
  without the variable. Validate the JSON and run the relevant gate after editing.

## Definition of done

A change is done only when the whole gate is green — never claim success before
it is. One command runs everything:

```bash
uv run terp verify --profile full   # the merge bar: exactly what CI enforces
```

Or run the four halves individually (useful for narrower reruns while iterating):

```bash
uv run pytest                         # backend gate (architecture, migrations, mounted modules)
npm --prefix frontend run typecheck   # frontend types (tsc)
npm --prefix frontend run lint        # frontend boundary lint + budget
npm --prefix frontend run build       # the production build CI ships
```

A frontend module that fails typecheck breaks the app at runtime (a blank page —
Vite refuses the module graph), so a red typecheck means the app does not work,
even if the backend gate passes. Import only what a package really exports:
check the catalog in `node_modules/@terp/react-core/README.md` instead of
guessing component names or props.

## Golden rules

1. Table models inherit `BaseTable`; never redeclare id/created_at/updated_at/version.
2. Services subclass `BaseService`; add read filters via `business_filters()` — it
   returns a *sequence of SQLAlchemy conditions* that are ANDed into every read
   (e.g. `return (Model.archived == False,)`), never a dict or keyword map; never
   override `base_query`.
3. Every write goes through the service; never call `session.add`/`commit` yourself.
4. Each module declares a `ModuleSpec` with a `Policy` (deny-by-default).
5. Routes set `response_model` to a Read DTO (never the table model); paginate with `Page[T]`.
6. Cap every input string with `Field(max_length=...)`.
7. Import only the `terp.core` public surface + declared capabilities.
8. Added or changed a database model? Generate its migration in the same change:
   `uv run terp migrate make <module_name>` (the app refuses to boot behind on
   migrations, and the test gate fails when migrations drift from the models).

## Frontend golden rules

Screens compose the **`@terp/react-core` component surface** — catalog in
`node_modules/@terp/react-core/README.md`; data collections via `DataView`
(`node_modules/@terp/react-core/src/dataview/README.md`); in-terminal recipes via
`uv run terp guide frontend` / `uv run terp guide dataview` / `uv run terp guide forms`.
The boundary lint enforces:
token-styled primitives only (no raw `<button>`/`<input>`/`<select>`/`<textarea>`/
`<table>`/`<dialog>`/`<form>`), the generated typed client only (no raw `fetch` /
`XMLHttpRequest` / `WebSocket` / `EventSource` / `sendBeacon`),
design-token styling with no `style={}` / `className` / module stylesheets (layout via
`Stack` / the page archetypes), in-app links via the router (no raw `<a href="/...">`),
and no deep `@terp/*` imports. Every routed view renders a page archetype (`Page` /
`OverviewPage` / `DetailPage` / `HubPage`) — the router refuses an unframed view.
This app also opts into the **`standard` layout contract** (ADR 0079,
`frontend/layout-contract.json` + `layoutContract` in `main.tsx` — keep the two in
sync): each archetype's body slot accepts only the contract's components (hub bodies:
`HubCard`; overview bodies: `DataView` / `ResourceList` + framework states; detail
bodies: `DetailList` / `Stack` / `Tabs` + framework states), checked at lint time
*and* at runtime — the plain `Page` stays free for bespoke screens, and every failure
message states the fix (`uv run terp guide layouts`).
Security defaults are refused too: `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` and DOM HTML-injection
sinks (render text, or `Markdown` for rich text), `eval()` / `new Function()`,
`javascript:` URLs, and a static `target="_blank"` without `rel="noopener"`.

No lint modes — every violation is an error. The governed opt-out is a justified
`// terp-allow-<rule>: <reason>` marker, counted exactly against
`frontend/escape-hatch-budget.json` (`npm run lint` runs the ratchet).

## Theming, language & the user menu (already wired)

- **Dark/light theme** — the token stylesheet ships both palettes; the sidebar user
  menu's theme toggle (light / dark / system) switches `<html data-theme>`. Because all
  styling is token-driven, modules never need theme-specific code. Re-theme the app by
  overriding the token values, never with inline colours.
- **Languages** — `frontend/src/main.tsx` declares the `locales` catalogs. Add a
  language by adding one entry (`{ label, strings }` overriding the framework strings);
  the user menu then shows a persisted language picker. Keep user-facing text in module
  code as `UiText` props so it follows the switch.
- **User menu** — every app gets the avatar menu (email, role, theme, language,
  sign-out) pinned to the sidebar bottom automatically; there is nothing to wire.

Add a module: `uv run terp new module <name>` → fill the slots → **mount it in
`app/main.py`** (import its `module`, add it to the `modules` list — unmounted
modules serve no routes) → `uv run terp migrate make <name>` →
`uv run terp openapi && npm --prefix frontend run generate` (typed client) →
`uv run terp check`.
